<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Schmognerova Addresses IMF on `Transformation' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Schmognerova Addresses IMF on `Transformation' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0105183494 Bratislava PRAVDA in Slovak 27 Apr 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> AU0105183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [TA SR report: "Unpopular Measures on the Horizon"] </F>
  [Text] Washington -- "The International Monetary Fund 
(IMF) should establish close contacts with the emerging World 
Trade Organization (WTO). We support the view that industrially 
advanced countries should limit trade barriers and, from the 
very beginning of this new trade era, open their economies more 
to states undergoing transformation," Deputy Prime Minister 
Brigita Schmognerova said at the annual IMF meeting in 
Washington yesterday. Her speech was the first by a 
representative of independent Slovakia at this forum. Together 
with Russian Deputy Prime Minister Aleksandr Shokhin, she 
represented the group of IMF states that are undergoing 
transformation. 
  Brigita Schmognerova said that latest experience testifies 
to 
the IMF's greater flexibility in relation to the need for the 
social acceptability of the transformation strategy. In this 
process, the IMF almost unilaterally emphasizes the formation of 
a social net, however, which places great demands on budget 
expenditures. These expenditures among the main causes of 
budget deficits, according to Schmognerova, rather than the 
subsidizing of state-owned companies. Vice President of the 
European Union (EU) Danny Christophersen explained the EU 
program to assist transforming states and the loan in support of 
macroeconomic stabilization. According to Deputy Prime Minister 
Brigita Schmognerova, Slovakia, too, will seek to obtain this 
credit from the EU. 
  "We assume that some consumer taxes will be changed and that 
the value-added tax for some products will be raised, which will 
be reflected in prices. The government would have to take these 
measures in the interest of eliminating the risks of the budget 
management, even if it did not strive to obtain the stand-by 
loan from the IMF," Brigita Schmognerova said after her talks 
with IMF Executive Director William Kiekens and head of the IMF 
mission to Slovakia Emmanuel Zervoudakis. 

</TEXT>

