<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Five Right-Wing Parties Consider Forming Bloc </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Five Right-Wing Parties Consider Forming Bloc </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2904200394 Bratislava SLOVENSKY DENNIK in Slovak 27 Apr 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU2904200394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava SLOVENSKY DENNIK </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "var": "United by Closeness"] </F>
  [Text] Bratislava--Representatives of the National 
Democratic Party, the Christian Democratic Movement, the 
Democratic Union of Slovakia, the Democratic Party, and the 
Party of Entrepreneurs and Tradesmen of the Slovak Republic met 
in the National Council of the Slovak Republic yesterday. They 
discussed the possibilities of forming a united right-wing bloc 
before the coming parliamentary elections. The parties agreed 
that, while being divided by their past, they are united by the 
closeness of their programs. The most hotly debated issues were 
the possible formation of a single electoral ticket, the 
possibilities of other parties joining in, and the formation of 
a bloc of civic accord [blok obcianskej dohody]. The parties 
are interested in the votes of their electoral base not getting 
lost. At the time of our going to press, the meeting of 
right-wing and liberal parties continued. 
  [Bratislava SME in Slovak on 27 April on page 1, under the 
headline "Meeting of Representatives of Five Political Parties," 
carries the following "sl, dos"-signed report: "Representatives 
of five political parties of the center and the right met in 
Bratislava yesterday. The TA SR published a report, according 
to which the meeting resulted in the formation of a preelection 
coalition--the Bloc of Civic Accord. According to our 
information, this report caused commotion among those present 
because the talks were still in progress at the time of its 
release. The attending parties--the Christian Democratic 
Movement, the Democratic Union of Slovakia, the Democratic 
Party, the Party of Entrepreneurs and Tradesmen, and the 
National Democratic Party--discussed their cooperation in the 
election campaign."] 

</TEXT>

