<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Continuing Strikes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Continuing Strikes </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Miller on `Incomprehensible' Strikes </H4>

<F P=102> LD3004085894 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 0800 
GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3004085894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Labor Minister Leszek Miller announced that even if 
Solidarity goes on strike as planned on 4 May, the government 
will be ready to continue negotiations on that day in the 
Trilateral Commission, composed of trade union, employer, and 
government representatives. 
  In a statement for the "Signals of the Day" program on 
Polish 
Radio First Program, Minister Miller recalled that, in 
accordance with yesterday's decisions by the Trilateral 
Commission, the talks on 4 May will concern the wage control 
law, the implementation of the State Enterprise Pact, and 
changes in tax regulations. These problems, Leszek Miller 
pointed out, recur in the trade union demands. 
  Minister Miller called yesterday's decision by the 
Solidarity's Protest Action Headquarters to hold strikes on 4, 
5, and 6 May incomprehensible. He stressed that implementation 
of the trade union demands can only be achieved through 
negotiation. According to Miller, the possible Solidarity 
strikes announced for next week can only hamper the talks in the 
Trilateral Commission. 

</TEXT>

