<H3> <TI>   Cernak Says 5 Right-Wing Parties To Cooperate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cernak Says 5 Right-Wing Parties To Cooperate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205144194 </F>
<F P=103> AU0205144194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] Slovak newspapers on 28 and 29 April 
publish reports on comments made by representatives of Slovak 
right-wing and center parties on the meeting of these parties' 
leaders in Bratislava on 26 April, which dealt with their 
cooperation in the election campaign. 
  Bratislava HOSPODARSKE NOVINY in Slovak on 28 April on page 
3 
carries a 200-word TA SR report on a news conference given by 
National Democratic Party-New Alternative Chairman Ludovit 
Cernak in Bratislava on 27 April. Cernak is quoted as saying 
that the five parties attending the 26 April meeting "showed 
interest in cooperating. They will agree on the form of this 
cooperation by the end of May at the latest." Cernak reportedly 
also said that all five parties "practically rejected the 
possibility of postelection cooperation with the Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia." 
  Bratislava SME in Slovak on 29 April on page 3 carries a 
200-word "dos"-signed report on a news conference given by the 
leadership of the Christian Democratic Movement (KDH) in 
Bratislava on 28 April. Speaking about the 26 April meeting of 
the leaders of "five right-wing and centrist parties," KDH 
Chairman Jan Carnogursky reportedly described it "as unlikely 
that all of these parties would contest the elections with a 
single slate of candidates. He supposes, however, that the 
number of slates of candidates will be under five." 

</TEXT>

