<H3> <TI>   Cernak Said To Own Compromising Documents </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cernak Said To Own Compromising Documents </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205171594 Bratislava PRAVDA in Slovak 29 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0205171594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Slovak National Party: Documents </F>
Disappeared"] 
  [Text] Bratislava--"Important documents that Ludovit 
Cernak signed as chairman of the Slovak National Party [SNS], 
along with Michal Kovac, when the latter was still a 
presidential candidate, have disappeared concurrently with 
Cernak's departure from the SNS. The publication of these 
documents would not necessarily cast a good light on the 
president's moral qualities and his credibility," Peter Sokol, 
adviser to the SNS chairman, said at an SNS briefing in 
Bratislava yesterday. He added that, within the framework of 
his election campaign, one day before his election, Michal Kovac 
had signed certain agreements, in which he pledged to the SNS to 
execute the office of the president in a certain way if he 
gained its support. According to Peter Sokol, in recalling 
former Minister of Foreign Affairs Milan Knazko, the president 
acted completely at variance with this pledge. "I have the 
justified suspicion that Mr. Cernak's possession of these 
documents may have a certain influence on the president's 
conduct," Peter Sokol said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

