<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Albanian `Paramilitary Units' Bought Stingers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Albanian `Paramilitary Units' Bought Stingers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904122594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1105 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2904122594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, 29 Apr (TANJUG) -- Albanian paramilitary 
units in Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- 
FYROM] were in possession of "Stinger" missiles before they were 
disbanded by the republic's Ministry of Internal Affairs in 
November 1993. 
  This was revealed today by VECER, a Skopje-based daily, 
which 
based its story on an account given by one of the main 
defendants, Hasan Agusi, former Yugoslav People's Army captain 
serving in the Marshall Tito barracks in Skopje until 1991. 
  According to Agusi, the Albanian paramilitary headquarters, 
which was based in Gostivar, paid 200,000 German marks to import 
weapons from Albania through Debar. The shipment consisted of 
200 Chinese-made Kalashnikovs. 

</TEXT>

