<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lack of Funds Restricts Role in `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lack of Funds Restricts Role in `Partnership' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205133794 Bratislava PRAVDA in Slovak 28 Apr 94 p 12 </F>
<F P=103> AU0205133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [TA SR report: "Military Commanders in Brussels"] </F>
  [Excerpts] Brussels--The chiefs of general staff of NATO 
member states met with their counterparts from the countries of 
the Eastern bloc yesterday to discuss plans connected with the 
Partnership for Peace project and participation in peace 
missions. [passage omitted] 
  "Slovakia is interested in participating in tactical and 
command and staff exercises of larger dimensions, but not this 
year," Slovak Army Commander Lieutenant General Julius Humaj, 
who represented the Slovak side, told the TA SR correspondent. 
For 1994, the Slovak Republic is preparing the exchange of 
smaller units, such as platoons and companies, at reciprocal 
exercises with other states of the North Atlantic Cooperation 
Council (NACC). "We cannot afford more, in view of the fact 
that only 1 percent of the Defense Ministry budget (that is, 104 
million Slovak korunas) has been earmarked for the 
implementation of the Partnership for Peace project," General 
Humaj noted. Julius Humaj also said that the Slovak Republic 
would present the presentation document for the Partnership for 
Peace program in May. "This document cannot be prepared in a 
few days or weeks," he said, reacting to comments by the NATO 
political leadership that the partner countries needed more time 
to draft the presentation document than had originally been 
expected. 
  Julius Humaj informed the NACC partners of the readiness of 
the Slovak Republic to make available, within the framework of 
Partnership for Peace, areas for training as well as training 
centers for the preparation of members of peacekeeping missions. 

</TEXT>

