<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daskalov on `Very Successful' Prague Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daskalov on `Very Successful' Prague Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2904144694 Sofia BTA in English 1346 GMT 29 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2904144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, April 29 (BTA) -- "My visit to the Czech 
Republic was very successful. Opportunities to intensify 
bilateral relations in different sectors are opening up," 
Foreign Minister Stanislav Daskalov said on his return from 
Prague today. His talks there focused on economic issues and 
the two countries' adjustment to the new environment. 
  Mr. Daskalov said work was in progress on the agreements on 
the avoidance of double taxation and on investment promotion. 
Bulgaria and the Czech Republic expressed willingness to hold 
talks on setting up a free trade zone which would allow 
businessmen to step up two-way trade. "Our problems are 
identical: Both countries want to become integrated into 
Europe," Mr. Daskalov said. The Czech officials showed an 
interest in Bulgaria's position on the situation in the former 
Yugoslavia, he said. 
  "I had an interesting meeting with Prime Minister Vaclav 
Klaus. Being one of the greatest experts in reforms, he was 
interested in their progress in Bulgaria, as well as in the 
political situation," Mr. Daskalov said. On commission of 
President Zhelyu Zhelev, he handed over to Czech President 
Vaclav Havel archive records on the 1968 events and Bulgaria's 
participation in them. This act was highly praised. "By the 
way, Bulgaria is the last country to deliver these documents and 
Czech journalists asked me why we had not done so earlier," Mr. 
Daskalov said. 
  The agreement on visa-free entry clearance signed in Prague 
allows Bulgarians to spend up to a month in Prague and return 
home quite pleased, Mr. Daskalov said. 
  While in Prague, the Bulgarian foreign minister was also 
received by Chairman of the Czech parliament Milan Uhde. 

</TEXT>

