<H3> <TI>   Council Approves Joint Military Exercises </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Council Approves Joint Military Exercises </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2904181794 Prague CTK in English 1721 GMT 29 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2904181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 29 (CTK) -- The parliament today 
approved a government proposal for foreign army units to be 
allowed to carry out short-term military exercises on Czech 
territory and for the Czech units to go abroad for similar 
exercises there. 
  The government is to inform the parliament about every 
exercise in advance and parliament is to give its prior approval 
each case foreign troops are to stay in this country. A maximum 
700 Czech troops may take part in the exercises abroad lasting 
up to 30 days, and up to 5,000 foreign troops may take part in 
exercises in the Czech Republic lasting up to 21 days, Defense 
Minister Antonin Baudys said. 
  The proposal limits the foreign countries (as venues for 
exercises and participants in exercises held on the Czech 
territory) to those that the Czech Republic wants to integrate 
into, those participating in the Partnership for Peace project, 
and European neutral countries. 
  Joint exercises will involve Czech units, staffs, and 
commanding officers in the training of humanitarian, search and 
rescue, and peace operations, and allow Czech Air Force and 
ground-based anti-aircraft units to receive training of a kind 
unavailable in the Czech Republic but necessary to maintain 
their combat readiness. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

