<F P=103> AU0305131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 3 (CTK) -- About 1.8 billion korunas 
($62 million) gained through the sales of surplus and 
unnecessary Army property were transferred to the state budget 
in 1993, Czech Defense Minister Antonin Baudys said at a press 
conference today. 
  He said he was pleased at the government's approval of the 
method of sales of Army buildings worth about 1 billion korunas 
($34,5 million). The Czech Army will get rid of this property 
either by transferring them free of charge to municipalities, in 
exchange for flats, or by selling them through real estate 
agencies, Baudys said. 
  The Army has been selling unnecessary buildings because it 
is 
impossible for it to continuously earmark soldiers for guarding 
them and money for their maintenance, Baudys explained. 

</TEXT>

