<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Sees `No Reason' To Meet With Klaus </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik Sees `No Reason' To Meet With Klaus </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205194994 Prague CTK in English 1843 GMT 2 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0205194994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, May 2 (CTK) -- Slovak Prime Minister 
Jozef Moravcik can see no reason to meet with his Czech 
counterpart Vaclav Klaus at the moment, government spokesman 
Lubomir Lintner told CTK today. He was reacting to a Friday [29 
April] statement by Slovak Finance Minister Rudolf Filkus that 
the two prime ministers should consider the abolition of the old 
bloc on the Slovak-Czech clearing account before it was 
discussed by the Slovak Government. 
  Lintner said that Moravcik was surprised by Filkus's 
statement, but added that "the times are hectic and a need for a 
meeting between the two premiers may arise as early as tomorrow." 
  Bratislava considers the abolition of the old bloc, which is 
used by enterprises in speculative payments to the detriment of 
Slovakia's balance of payments, the most urgent issue in 
relations with Prague. Under the old bloc, the 1-1 ratio is 
applied in payments related to trade agreements concluded before 
the currency split on February 8, 1993. The new bloc uses ECUs. 
  The Czech Government approved a proposal to abolish the old 
bloc as early as in mid-April, but the Slovak Government 
recently returned a similar draft for rewriting and it has not 
reappeared on the government's agenda to date. 

</TEXT>

