<H3> <TI>   Egyutteles Leader on Joining European Charter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Egyutteles Leader on Joining European Charter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0305133494 Prague CTK in English 1148 GMT 3 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0305133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, May 3 (CTK) -- Miklos Duray, chairman 
of the Egyutteles (Coexistence) Hungarian minority movement in 
Slovakia, said today that the current cabinet of Jozef Moravcik 
had been charged by parliament with joining the European Charter 
of Regional and Minority Languages. He said that a failure to 
meet this condition might influence Egyutteles' support for the 
government coalition. 
  "I know nothing about the proposal to sign the European 
Charter of Minority Languages having been withdrawn," Duray told 
CTK, adding that while discussing the government program the 
parliament charged the government with joining the charter. 
This had been demanded by Egyutteles for at least two years, 
already during the former Czechoslovakia, he said. 
  The Slovak Government press department today told CTK that 
the proposal for the signing of the charter had been withdrawn 
from the agenda of today's cabinet meeting. 
  However, the government today approved a parliamentary 
proposal on population registers. The passing of this proposal 
was one of further demands by Hungarian minority leaders as it 
was to include the use of Hungarian first names and Hungarian 
women's names without the Slovak ending -ova. Meeting this 
demand was also one of the conditions which Slovakia committed 
itself to fulfilling when it was accepted to the Council of 
Europe. 

</TEXT>

