<H3> <TI>   Bohunice Nuclear Plant Not To Close Until 2002 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bohunice Nuclear Plant Not To Close Until 2002 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205201394 Prague CTK in English 1919 GMT 2 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0205201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, May 2 (CTK) -- The economy ministers 
consider that the gradual reconstruction of the V-1 unit of the 
nuclear power plant in Jaslovske Bohunice, west Slovakia, can be 
carried out so that it will not close until after the year 2002, 
announced Economy Minister Peter Magvasi. "The decision comes 
from the recommendation of the International Agency for Atomic 
Energy (MAAE) [IAEA], which rates highly the technical state of 
the V-1 reactor in Bohunice. The agency recommended such action 
as would allow for V-1 to operate until the year 2002," he said, 
adding however that the cabinet had yet to decide the issue. 
Earlier it was said that if not reconstructed, the plant would 
have to close down in 1995. A Franco-German consortium and the 
EBRD are making the provision of a 1.3-billion mark loan for the 
uncompleted nuclear energy plant at Mochovce, west Slovakia, 
conditional on the closure of the V-1 plant. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

