<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatian Leader Rejects Unitary Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Croatian Leader Rejects Unitary Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205212494 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2000 GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205212494 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Leaders of the Croat republic of Herceg-Bosna, led 
by Kresimir Zubak, president of the presidential council, 
visited the area of Rama and Uskoplje today. Zdenko Vranjes 
reports: 
  [Vranjes] The need to strengthen the institution of the 
law-governed state and to suppress crime and smuggling in 
Herceg-Bosna was the focus of attention of the talks between the 
political leaders of the Croat republic of Herceg-Bosna and 
civilian and military authorities of the Rama and Uskoplje 
municipalities and the priests of Rama monastery. It was 
emphasized that the passage of humanitarian and other convoys 
should be made more orderly. All convoys for Bosnia pass 
through Rama and Uskoplje. Their chaotic passage causes even 
greater and more dangerous disorder, robberies, and attacks by 
rebel groups, it was said at the talks. 
  The implementation of the Washington agreement was discussed 
at the session of the Croatian Democratic Union municipal 
committee and the command of the Ante Starcevic Brigade from 
Uskoplje. More work needs to be done on the border delineation 
between the cantons, it was stressed. 
  Zubak reiterated that the Croatian people have truly 
accepted 
the Washington agreement as a step toward peace. He described 
Alija Izetbegovic's letter [to Tudjman] yesterday as an attempt 
to shift to the Croatian people the blame for the lack of 
readiness to implement the Washington agreement. 
  Zubak said the Croatian representatives will not allow the 
Croatian people to be deceived. They will not allow certain 
circles among the Muslim people to establish a unitary 
Bosnia-Herzegovina by bypassing the essence of the Washington 
agreement. Such attempts can be detected in the demands by 
Muslim representatives for both the president of the federation 
and the prime minister to be Muslims. We will not accept this, 
for such demands have no basis in the constitution of the new 
federation, Zubak said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

