<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reasons for Delay in Tudjman Visit Examined </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reasons for Delay in Tudjman Visit Examined </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205160994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0205160994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nada al-Isa from Zagreb] </F>
  [Text] Why has Croatian President Franjo Tudjman still not 
paid a visit to Sarajevo, even though President Izetbegovic has 
asked him on two occasions. Is the UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR] behind this? Are UNPROFOR generals preventing the 
Croatian president's visit to Sarajevo and the forming of the 
Croat-Bosnian federation? The question is not entirely 
unfounded, and here is why. During a recent interview for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Radio and Television, in the course of a 
private, very engaging conversation, and in response to my 
question why he still has not visited Sarajevo, the Croatian 
president literally said: You have to ask UNPROFOR why I still 
have not been to Sarajevo -- therefore, firsthand information 
from the highest place in Croatia. Moreover, it is also 
possible to hear the following on the Croatian political scene: 
Now that they have tragically solved the fate of Gorazde, 
UNPROFOR generals may be [words indistinct] and we can expect 
all kinds of things from them, even the prevention of a 
normalization of relations between Croatia and 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  However, there is yet another question to which it is 
currently impossible to get an answer in Zagreb. Why has the 
Croatian media published an AFP report on President 
Izetbegovic's latest letter once again inviting President 
Tudjman to visit Sarajevo? Why was there no public statement 
from the presidential palace, which is the usual procedure? Was 
the letter intended only for Dr. Tudjman's private perusal, 
which is how a Croatian opposition member picturesquely 
commented on this. Is it really only UNPROFOR that is 
preventing Tudjman's visit to Sarajevo, or is there a lack of 
goodwill in the presidential palace? 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

