<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dlouhy Refutes Criticism of Customs Union </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dlouhy Refutes Criticism of Customs Union </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305172994 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1600 
GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0305172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The customs union and the payment agreement with the 
Czech Republic were disadvantageous in many respects for 
Slovakia, declared Slovak Deputy Prime Minister Brigita 
Schmoeglerova. According to the deputy prime minister, the 
Czechs could not be blamed for this state of affairs. On the 
contrary, the blame was attached to the former Slovak 
Government, which was not well prepared for negotiations that 
led to the conclusion of the agreements. 
  Vladimir Dlouhy, Czech minister of industry and trade, had 
this to say to Czech Radio on the subject: 
  [Begin Dlouhy recording] I would need to know her comments 
in 
total. My opinion is, however, that the customs union is 
advantageous for both sides because it has opened up markets for 
us more than if we did not have one. I would not like to enter 
into a discussion about the payment agreement--which, according 
to press reports, was also contained in the comments made by the 
deputy prime minister--but, regarding the customs union, I am 
100-percent certain that it is advantageous for both sides. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

